[{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question. (15 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two vertical, parallel plates that are a distance of d apart. The vertical plate on the left has a potential of positive V, and the vertical plate on the right has a potential of 0. A region of magnetic field exists to the right of the righthand plate. A particle that has a mass of m and a charge of positive q is shown just to the right of the lefthand plate. The dashed path of the particle shows it moving straight to the right and exiting through a hole in the center of the righthand plate. The path then continues into the magnetic field, curving downwards in a semicircle and ending when it reaches the righthand plate at a location below the hole.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252431.g06.png\"/></div>\n<div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\">A potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase V\"><math alttext=\"uppercase V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> exists between two parallel plates that are separated by a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. A particle of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\"><math alttext=\"m\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive q\"><math alttext=\"positive q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is accelerated from rest through the potential difference, and as a result moves between the plates in a straight line in the plane of the page, as shown above. The particle reaches the right-hand plate with a speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase v\"><math alttext=\"lowercase v\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, passes through a hole in the plate, and enters a region containing a uniform magnetic field. The particle then follows the semicircular path shown. Gravitational effects are negligible.</p></div></div>\n</div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Would the speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase v\"><math alttext=\"lowercase v\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> of the particle be greater, smaller, or the same if the mass of the particle was greater? Explain your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"},{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) A student derives the equation <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase v equals, the fraction with numerator 2 times q, times uppercase V, and denominator m times d, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"lowercase v equals, the fraction with numerator 2 times q, times uppercase V, and denominator m times d, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> for the speed of the particle. Whether or not the equation is correct, is it consistent with your answer to part (a)? Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"},{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) A student equates the following two expressions to determine how an increase in the particle’s speed affects the radius of its path in the magnetic field.</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\"><li class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m times lowercase v squared, divided by r\"><math alttext=\"m times lowercase v squared, divided by r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> for the magnitude of the net force on an object in uniform circular motion with radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r\"><math alttext=\"r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></li><li class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"q times lowercase v, times B\"><math alttext=\"q times lowercase v, times B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> for the magnitude of the force on a charged particle in a magnetic field of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></li></ul><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Describe the relationship between the particle’s speed and the radius of its path indicated by these expressions, and indicate how an increase in speed affects the radius.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"},{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Another student writes the equation <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r squared equals, the fraction with numerator 2 times uppercase V, times m, and denominator q times B squared, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"r squared equals, the fraction with numerator 2 times uppercase V, times m, and denominator q times B squared, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>V</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>q</mi><msup><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> for the radius of the path as a function of the potential difference between the two parallel plates. Whether or not the equation is correct, is it consistent with your answer to part (c)? Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"},{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:E part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"E\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) An electric field can be applied in the region containing the magnetic field that will cause the particle to move through the region in a straight line. What is the direction of such an electric field? Justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"},{"id":"VR252431","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:F part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"F\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two vertical, parallel plates that are a distance of d apart. The vertical plate on the left has a potential of positive V, and the vertical plate on the right has a potential of 0. A particle that has a mass of m and a charge of positive q is shown just to the right of the lefthand plate, and its path between the plates is a straight dashed line to the right, ending at a hole in the center of the righthand plate. Some distance to the right of the righthand plate and above the hole is a wire that is perpendicular to the page with a current directed into the page. Coordinate axes are shown on the far right, with positive x to the right, positive y toward the top of the page, and positive z out of the page.\" height=\"283\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252431.g03.png\" width=\"450\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The region of the magnetic field is replaced by a wire that is perpendicular to the page and has a current directed into the page (as shown above). The particle still moves in a straight line between the plates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) With respect to the coordinate axes shown, in what direction is the acceleration of the particle at the instant it passes through the hole? Explain your reasoning.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252431_rubric"}]